title: ADVANCED TRIGONOMETRY (Solutions of ∆)📍 LESSON 7 📍In ∆ ABC, prove: a sin ½ (B-C) = (b-c) cos½A.
description:
In this math tutorial our task is to prove the problem using the fact that the L.H.S = R.H.S.
Using the R.H.S to derive the L.H.S the following key concepts can be explored:
Basic Concepts:
Sine Rule: a/sin A = b/sin B = c/ sin C.
Equating: a/sinA and b/ sinB ,then b= asinB/sinA
Equating a/sinA= c/sinC,then c =a sinC/sin A.
• Sum-to-product identity:
sinB - sinC= 2cos½(B+C)sin½(B-C)
• Half angle formula for sinA: sinA = 2 sin½A cos½A.
•sin½(B+C) = sin(90⁰ - ½A)= cos½A.
